Golconda is built on a 400 foothill. It had 3 lines of massive fortification walls, one within the other, rising above 12 metres in height. A deep moat with a circumference of 7km sourrounded the fort and the town. There were 8 imposing gateways, 84 bastions rising upto 18 metres in height mounted with cannons of varying caliber. This fort was impregnable in the medieval deccan. The defeat of the kakitiyas by the Delhi Sultanate in the early 14th century saw the saw the appointment of governers to rule these areas. One of the governers, Bahaman Shah revolted against the sultanate and formed the Bahmani Sultanate in the Deccan Sultanate. After the death of Mohammed Shah Bahaman, the deccan sultanate broke up into five principalities, Ahmednagar, Berar, Bijapur, Bidar and Golconda. Sultan Quli, the subedar and governor of Golconda declared himself independent and laid the foundation of a new dyansty, Qutub Shahi dynasty in 1550AD.
